p.q:
That—
(a) income tax for the year 1970–71 shall be charged, in the case of an individual whose total income exceeded £2,500, at the same higher rates in respect of the excess of that income over £2,000 as were charged for the year 1969–70;
(b) an individual whose total income did not exceed £2,681 shall be entitled to have the surtax chargeable by virtue of paragraph (a) above reduced to an amount equal to 40 per cent. of the difference between his total income and £2,500. And it is hereby declared that it is expedient in the public interest that this Resolution should have statutory effect under the provisions of the Provisional Collection of Taxes Act 1968.—[Mr. Barber.]

That the following alterations shall be made in Chapter II of Part I of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1970—


(a) in section 9(1) (earned income relief) for paragraph (b) there shall be substituted—


"(b) 15 per cent. of the amount of any excess of his earned income over £4,005";

(b) in section 10(3) (appropriate amount for child)—


(i) for £165 (child over 16) there shall be substituted £205;

(ii) for £140 (child over 11 but not over 16) there shall be substituted £180; and

(iii) for £115 (child not over 11) there shall be substituted £155;



(c) in section 9 (age relief)—


(i) in subsection (2) for the words from "either he" to "his wife living with him" there shall be substituted the word "he", and

(ii) after subsection (3) there shall be inserted the following subsection—

(d) in section 7 (relief for persons over sixty-five with small incomes)—


(i) for the references to £475 and £740 (income limits for exemption) there shall be substituted references to £504 and £786;

(ii) for the reference to £255 (the excess over those limits beyond which relief by reduction of tax is excluded) there shall be substituted a reference to £330.

That, in respect of each contribution week within the meaning of Part VI of the Finance Act 1966 beginning on or after 5th July 1971 the amount payable by way of selective employment tax in respect of any person shall be reduced—


(a) if that person is a man over the age of eighteen, to £1·20;

(b) if that person is a woman over the age of eighteen, to £0·60;

(c) if that person is a boy under the age of eighteen, to £0·60; and

(d) if that person is a girl under the age of eighteen, to £0·40.

That, notwithstanding anything to the contrary in the practice of the House relating to the matters which may be included in Finance Bills, any Finance Bill of the present Session may contain the following provisions taking effect in a future year—


(a) provisions for a new method of charging income tax, fixing a rate for the tax to be charged by the new method, abolishing certain reliefs from surtax and allowing the payment of part of any surtax to be deferred;

(b) provisions for charging a wife's earnings as if she were not married;

(c) provisions for or in connection with the repeal of Chapter V of Part I of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1970 (aggregation of child's investment etc. income with income of parent);

(d) provisions for or in connection with the exclusion of all unmarried children from


Chapter II of Part XVI of that Act (settlements by parents) on their attaining the age of eighteen;

(e) provisions about occupational pension schemes;

(f) provisions for requiring sums on account of income tax to be deducted from payments under certain contracts relating to construction operations; and

(g) provisions amending section 15 of the Finance Act 1970 (which increased initial allowances for industrial buildings and structures).—[Mr. Barber.]
